{"key":"post-20292402","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>20292402</id>\n<content>Any time a coir substrate contaminates on first flush, it was the spawn.&amp;nbsp; You can use coir unpasteurized, although 'cooking' it helps the mycelium get going.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Thus, it' not your dirty fingernails or other issues, but dirty grain spawn.&amp;nbsp; I've made my views on shumvbox known, but of course others disagree.&amp;nbsp; Another possibility is you're using lime from a dolomite source.&amp;nbsp; If so, it probably has Mg over 2% to 3%, which can impede mushroom mycelium, giving mold a break.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gypsum helps to alleviate pH swings, but it's not really a buffer.&amp;nbsp; Besides, mushroom mycelium prefers a somewhat acidic substrate.&amp;nbsp; Gypsum mostly helps supply calcium and sulfur, both essential to robust fruit development.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>20292410</next>\n<prev>20292393</prev>\n<first>20291687</first>\n<last>20643574</last>\n<when>1405723368</when>\n<utime>07/19/14 01:42 AM</utime>\n</post>"}